defaultSyria
default’s chemical weapons. Therefore, it was seen to work, and we will carry on the momentum and see if we can get something on 
defaultIran
default’s nuclear programme separately. It provides a certain amount of foreign policy success, but it will probably be longer and harder than some in the White House have considered.
defaultQ79 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultHendrickdefault:default You said it from the 
defaultUS
default side. What about looking at it from the Iranian side?
defaultProfessor defaultAnsaridefault:default The Iranians are being driven mostly—at the higher echelons with 
defaultKhamenei
default and the others—by sanctions relief. It is the economy. There are many people in 
defaultIran
default, although not necessarily in power, who see it as a necessity to have some sort of relationship with the 
defaultUnited States
default—you don’t have to love them, but you should have relations with them. I have to say that the Russians might have something to say about it, but there is a bit of the great game going on there. 
defaultStrictly speaking, in the upper echelons, Syria and so on are all continuing conflicts, but what they are really focused on is at least moving that potential for conflict over the nuclear issue on to a different track, getting some sanctions relief and getting the economy back on a level footing. That is what is driving them. I do not think that it is really driven by aspirations to have better relations overall with the 
defaultUnited States
default—unfortunately, I should say.
